# Movie Industry Trend Analysis using Python

## Business Context
Studios, producers, and streaming platforms rely on historical performance patterns to guide investment, casting, and genre strategies.
This project analyzes movie data from 1916â€“2016 to uncover drivers of ratings, profitability, and audience preferences.

---

## Objective
To extract actionable insights from historical movie data by performing structured data preparation, transformation, and exploratory analysis.

---

## Dataset
Movie dataset spanning ~100 years including:
- Ratings
- Revenue and profit indicators
- Directors
- Actors
- Genres

---

## Tools & Libraries
- Python  
- Pandas  
- NumPy  
- Matplotlib 

---

## Analytical Workflow

### Data Understanding
- Loaded and validated dataset  
- Reviewed structure, columns, and data types  

### Data Cleaning
- Identified and handled missing values  
- Removed unnecessary columns  
- Dropped duplicates  
- Standardized formats and units  
- Verified retained records after cleaning  

### Analysis Performed
- Identified movies with highest profit
- Extracted IMDb Top 250
- Determined top-performing directors
- Analyzed most popular genres
- Found critic-favorite vs audience-favorite actors

---

## Key Insights
- A small number of films generate disproportionately high profits, with big-budget productions dominating the top ranks.
- James Cameron appears multiple times among the highest-profit movies, reinforcing the repeat impact of established blockbuster directors.
- When filtering by both rating quality and sufficient audience votes, the IMDb Top 250 list highlights how popularity and credibility must coexist.
- Damien Chazelle ranks among the top directors by average IMDb score, showing consistent critical performance.
- Genre combinations matter: Family and Sci-Fi repeatedly emerge as one of the strongest audience-pulling mixes.
- Among the compared actors, Leonardo DiCaprio stands out as both a critic favorite and an audience favorite.

